{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413953"},"attributes":{"position":29,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:34:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:34:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11518"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510316"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11518"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11518"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.45,0.05,0.04,0.09,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60492"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45917"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42618"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60492"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up. He has a history of heart failure with reduced ejection fraction (left ventricular ejection fraction 35%). His medical history includes hypertension and dyslipidaemia. His current medications include perindopril, metoprolol, spironolactone, and furosemide. He reports stable symptoms with New York Heart Association (NYHA) class II symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 65/min, blood pressure 118/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is mild ankle oedema bilaterally. Heart sounds are dual with no murmurs, and chest is clear to auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following changes to the medication regime would provide the most mortality benefit?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Add empagliflozin","Add gliclazide","Add digoxin","Increase furosemide dosage","Add hydrochlorothiazide"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe four pillars of heart failure therapy that reduce mortality are ACE inhibitors/ARBs, beta blockers, mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists, and SGLT2 inhibitors. This patient is already on the first three, and adding an SGLT2 inhibitor like empagliflozin would complete the regimen and provide the most mortality benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E is a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitor that has been shown to reduce mortality in patients with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, regardless of whether they have diabetes. Adding empagliflozin to this patient\u0027s regimen would provide significant mortality benefit, complementing the existing heart failure therapies he is on.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGliclazide\u003C/strong\u003E is an oral hypoglycaemic agent used in the management of type 2 diabetes. It does not have a role in the management of heart failure and would not provide mortality benefit in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigoxin\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in heart failure to control symptoms, particularly in patients with atrial fibrillation, but it does not provide a mortality benefit. It is not indicated in this patient who is stable and in sinus rhythm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing the furosemide dosage\u003C/strong\u003E may help manage symptoms of fluid overload, such as oedema, but it does not provide a mortality benefit. Diuretics are primarily used for symptomatic relief in heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E is a thiazide diuretic that can be used for hypertension or mild fluid retention, but it does not provide mortality benefit in heart failure. It is not indicated in this patient\u0027s current management plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitors reduce mortality in heart failure with reduced ejection fraction, regardless of diabetes status.","SGLT2 inhibitors should be considered in all patients with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction who are already on standard therapy.","The four pillars of heart failure therapy that reduce mortality are ACE inhibitors/ARBs, beta blockers, mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists, and SGLT2 inhibitors."],"references":["Yancy CW, Januzzi JL Jr, Allen LA, et al. 2017 ACC Expert Consensus Decision Pathway for Optimization of Heart Failure Treatment: Answers to 10 Pivotal Issues About Heart Failure With Reduced Ejection Fraction: A Report of the American College of Cardiology Task Force on Expert Consensus Decision Pathways. J Am Coll Cardiol 2018; 71:201.","Ponikowski P, Voors AA, Anker SD, et al. 2016 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure: The Task Force for the diagnosis and treatment of acute and chronic heart failure of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC)Developed with the special contribution of the Heart Failure Association (HFA) of the ESC. Eur Heart J 2016; 37:2129.","Yancy CW, Jessup M, Bozkurt B, et al. 2013 ACCF/AHA guideline for the management of heart failure: executive summary: a report of the American College of Cardiology Foundation/American Heart Association Task Force on practice guidelines. Circulation 2013; 128:1810.","Vaduganathan M, Docherty KF, Claggett BL, Jhund PS, de Boer RA, Hernandez AF, Inzucchi SE, Kosiborod MN, Lam CSP, Martinez F, Shah SJ, Desai AS, McMurray JJV, Solomon SD. SGLT-2 inhibitors in patients with heart failure: a comprehensive meta-analysis of five randomised controlled trials. Lancet. 2022 Sep 3;400(10354):757-767. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(22)01429-5. Epub 2022 Aug 27. Erratum in: Lancet. 2023 Jan 14;401(10371):104. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(23)00018-1. PMID: 36041474.","Atherton JJ, Sindone A, De Pasquale CG, Driscoll A, MacDonald PS, Hopper I, et al. National heart foundation of Australia and cardiac society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the prevention, detection, and management of heart failure in Australia 2018. Heart, Lung and Circulation [Internet]. 2018;27(10):1123\u2013208. Available from: https://www.heartlungcirc.org/article/S1443-9506(18)31777-3/fulltext#secsect0320","\u200c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45917"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11518"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45917"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-12T20:12:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-12T20:13:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4149"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60492"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio